

---
const pageTitle = "The Serpent";
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <title>{pageTitle}</title>
    <style>
      :root {
        --paper: #ffffff;
        --ink: #000000;
        --line: #000000;
        --soft: #efefef;
        --blue: #0000ee;
        --red: #cc0000;
        --green: #008000;
      }

      html, body {
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
        background: var(--paper);
        color: var(--ink);
        font-family: "Times New Roman", Times, serif;
        font-size: 18px;
        line-height: 1.55;
      }

      a { text-decoration: underline; }
      a.blue { color: var(--blue); }
      a.red { color: var(--red); }
      a.green { color: var(--green); }

      .page {
        width: min(900px, calc(100% - 48px));
        margin: 0 auto;
        padding: 28px 0 60px;
      }

      .topbar {
        border: 1px solid var(--line);
        padding: 10px 14px;
        margin-bottom: 18px;
        text-align: center;
        background: #fafafa;
      }

      .topbar span {
        display: inline-block;
        margin: 0 8px;
        white-space: nowrap;
      }

      .frame {
        border: 1px solid var(--line);
        padding: 22px 24px 28px;
        position: relative;
        overflow: hidden;
      }

      .symbol-bg {
        position: absolute;
        top: 50%;
        left: 50%;
        transform: translate(-50%, -50%) rotate(-6deg);
        font-size: 250px;
        opacity: 0.12;
        pointer-events: none;
        user-select: none;
        z-index: 0;
      }

      .content-layer {
        position: relative;
        z-index: 1;
      }

      h1 {
        font-size: 40px;
        line-height: 1.05;
        text-align: center;
        margin: 0 0 8px;
        font-weight: bold;
      }

      .subtitle {
        text-align: center;
        font-size: 16px;
        margin: 0 0 24px;
      }

      .divider {
        text-align: center;
        margin: 18px 0 24px;
        letter-spacing: 1px;
      }

      p { margin: 0 0 16px; }

      .quote {
        margin: 22px auto;
        max-width: 680px;
        border: 1px solid var(--line);
        padding: 14px 16px;
        background: var(--soft);
        font-style: italic;
        text-align: center;
      }

      .section-title {
        font-size: 28px;
        text-align: center;
        margin: 34px 0 16px;
        font-weight: bold;
      }

      .mini-links {
        text-align: center;
        margin-top: 30px;
        font-size: 16px;
      }

      .mini-links a {
        display: inline-block;
        margin: 4px 10px;
      }

      .footer-note {
        text-align: center;
        margin-top: 26px;
        font-size: 14px;
      }

      @media (max-width: 700px) {
        html, body { font-size: 17px; }
        h1 { font-size: 32px; }
        .frame { padding: 18px 16px 24px; }
        .symbol-bg { font-size: 180px; }
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="page">
      <div class="topbar">
        <span>[ <a class="blue" href="/">home</a> ]</span>
        <span>[ <a class="blue" href="/symbols/">symbols index</a> ]</span>
        <span>[ <a class="green" href="/symbols/fool">previous</a> ]</span>
        <span>[ <a class="red" href="/symbols/tree-of-life">next</a> ]</span>
      </div>

      <main class="frame">
        <div class="symbol-bg">🐍</div>

        <div class="content-layer">
          <h1>The Serpent</h1>
          <p class="subtitle">symbols / instinct / renewal / archive entry 003</p>

          <div class="divider">***</div>

          <p>
            The serpent is one of the most ancient and complex symbols. It moves close
            to the ground, hidden, silent, and precise. Because of this, it is often
            associated with instinct, danger, and forces that lie beneath conscious control.
          </p>

          <p>
            In many traditions, the serpent represents both threat and wisdom. It can
            poison, but it can also heal. It sheds its skin, making it a symbol of
            renewal, transformation, and cycles of death and rebirth.
          </p>

          <div class="quote">
            what is feared as dangerous may also carry the power to transform.
          </div>

          <h2 class="section-title">instinct and depth</h2>

          <p>
            Psychologically, the serpent points to instinctual life. These are forces
            that move before thought, beneath control, and often outside moral framing.
            When ignored, they can appear as anxiety, compulsion, or threat.
          </p>

          <p>
            When brought into awareness, these same forces can become sources of vitality,
            perception, and grounded intelligence.
          </p>

          <h2 class="section-title">shedding and renewal</h2>

          <p>
            The shedding of skin makes the serpent a symbol of transformation that does
            not come from adding, but from releasing. Something old must fall away so
            something new can emerge.
          </p>

          <p>
            This process can feel unsettling. The familiar identity loosens, and for a
            time there is exposure. But this is often necessary for growth.
          </p>

          <div class="mini-links">
            <a class="blue" href="/symbols/">back to symbols index</a>
            <a class="blue" href="/symbols/tree-of-life">continue to: tree of life</a>
            <a class="red" href="/symbols/fool">fool</a>
          </div>

          <p class="footer-note">
            this page is part of the hidden archive.
          </p>
        </div>
      </main>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>